  "prompt": "How come Harry can see the Thestrals after his fourth year and not before that?",
  "response": "Harry couldn't see the Thestrals before the end of his fourth year, even though he had witnessed his mother's death as a baby, because **you can only see Thestrals when you fully understand and accept the concept of death**.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why:\n\n*   **Witnessing Death is Necessary, But Not Sufficient:** Harry witnessed his mother's death as an infant, but babies don't have the cognitive ability to process and comprehend what death truly means. It's traumatic, but not fully understood.\n\n*   **Cedric Diggory's Death Provided Understanding:** The death of Cedric Diggory at the end of the Triwizard Tournament was the first time Harry truly *understood* death. He saw it happen, he witnessed the finality of it, and he felt the grief and loss connected with it. This understanding, rather than just the act of witnessing, is what unlocked his ability to see Thestrals.\n\nIn short, seeing death is not enough. You have to understand and come to terms with it, and Harry wasn't able to do that until Cedric died.",
